\begin_layout Section
Research
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Research
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Research"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Scientist's Science! Power
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Science Power
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is slightly special, in that it starts off as a slightly weaker power and
 can be upgraded during the course of an adventure by doing Research into
 the nature of whatever the PCs are facing in order to tailor the power
 specifically to what's currently necessary.
 There are three variations: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Starting with an Ultra-Flexible power that can do most anything but is at
 low level and can Power Up through Research to a higher level; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Starting with a high level Power that has one specific use and can Power
 Up
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Power Up!Research and
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to Ultra-Flexible; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Starting with medium power and flexibility that can Power Up to full power
 and Ultra-Flexible
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Science Power!Ultra-Flexible
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all three variations, the procedure for doing Research remains the same:
 you must, over the course of the adventure, engage in 
\series bold
three
\series default
 separate scenes that revolve around your character and your allies doing
 the necessary Research into the device or scientific principle you're trying
 to create, using your Research Shtick.
 In most cases the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Science Research Shtick
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Research Shtick
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shticks!Research
\end_layout

\end_inset

 should work without a roll.
 If a roll
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Research!When to roll
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is required because the player is unsure whether their type of science
 really can accomplish what they're aiming to do (say a neuroscientist whose
 powers operate on brains is trying to research a device to deactivate a
 robot), the GM should assign a difficulty based on the power level of the
 target; if the roll fails, the Scientist can't try again in that scene,
 and will have to come up with some other approach to moving the research
 forward or a different sort of device.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, you might have a scene where you and possibly your allies
 are using the ship's computer records to identify the creature attacking
 the colonists; a scene where you go to the mine where the colonists were
 attacked to recover alien tissues that the device requires; and a scene
 where you use the ship's lab and that tissue to create a device capable
 of paralyzing the creature.
 The exact nature of the scenes should be determined during play, through
 the players and GM deciding what's plausible given what's been going on
 so far, rather than a cookie-cutter approach: computer library, tissue,
 lab.
 It's justifying what your character is doing as an occasion to employ the
 Research Shtick; the requirement that there be three such scenes and that
 the scenes be different is just to prevent every adventure from turning
 into a wait while the Scientist character hangs around in the ship's lab
 until the device is ready.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you perform three successful scenes in which you are doing research
 (scenes where the focus is research and you score a success with your Research
 Shtick if necessary), your device is ready, and you announce what it does.
 It should be one very specific effect, such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Shrink giant insects
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

paralyze methane-breathing creatures.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 While you should be researching during this time, that doesn't mean you
 can't participate in scenes.
 You can put down your tools and zap the creature attacking you in the lab,
 or go out to the scene of the crime and collect scientific samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you decide a roll ought to be required other PCs can assist you by using
 their investigative abilities to perform relevant research.
 The difficulty is set to be the base power level of the intended target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Advantages And Disadvantages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:AdvantagesAndDisadvantages"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Advantages and Disadvantages
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Advantages are aspects that make a Ability more useful, and Disadvantages
 are things that makes it less useful.
 For instance if a Ability is exceptionally Flexible so that almost anything
 can be justified according to the Primary Rule, that's an Advantage; if
 a Ability has a more limited use than normal, for instance it can only
 be used to defend against cold-based attacks, that's a Disadvantage.
 There are both Big and Small Advantages and Disadvantages (labeled AA and
 A, or DD and D), and their effects on a Ability are cumulative.
 A Small Advantage on a Ability costs one Boost, a Big Advantage costs 2,
 a Small Disadvantage gives you an extra Boost to spend on that Ability,
 and a Big Disadvantage gives you two extra Boosts on that Ability (you
 may not take a Disadvantage on a Ability in order to get Boosts to spend
 on some other Ability or Attribute).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Advantages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Advantages"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Advantages
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Abilities!Advantages
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Advantages represent some quality of the Ability that makes it more useful.
 You should only give the Ability an advantage if it represents a significant
 increase in the Ability.
 Many little side effects that might be advantageous under some circumstances
 are already covered by the description.
 For instance, if you have a Sleep Gas Ability it isn't necessary to take
 Exotic even though it's implied that something like a Shield or Tough Hide
